010, 80 minutes.\n\n{{Chinese mythology}}\n{{Religion in China}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chinese Folk Religion}}\n[[Category:Chinese folk religion| ]]\n[[Category:East Asian religions]]\n[[Category:Folk religion]]\n", "name_user": "ChinaVirus-19", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Minor edits)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_folk_religion"}
{"title_page": "Kazumi Totaka", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Totaka|the acharya named Totaka|Totakacharya}}\n{{Japanese name|Totaka}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Kazumi Totaka\n| image            = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1967|8|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| instrument       = [[Piano]], [[guitar]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], [[vibraphone]]\n| genre            = [[Video game music]], [[jazz]]\n| occupation       = Composer, sound director, voice actor\n| years_active     = 1990&ndash;present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| native_name      = \u6238\u9ad8\u4e00\u751f\n| Notable work     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Kazumi Totaka'''|\u6238\u9ad8 \u4e00\u751f|Totaka Kazumi|born August 23, 1967}}<ref>{{cite book |title=Nintendo Official Guide Book \u2013 The Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening |chapter=\u300c\u30bc\u30eb\u30c0\u306e\u4f1d\u8aac \u5922\u3092\u307f\u308b\u5cf6\u300d\u958b\u767a\u30b9\u30bf\u30c3\u30d5\u540d\u9451 |language=Japanese |page=120 |date=July 1993 |isbn=4-09-102448-3 |publisher=[[Shogakukan|Shogakukan Inc]]}}</ref> is a Japanese [[video game music|video game composer]] and sound director who is best known for his various compositions in many [[Nintendo]] games. He occasionally does voice acting as well, including [[Yoshi]] from the ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' series. He also directed the development of ''[[Wii Music]]\"\n\n==Works==\n\n===Composer===\n*''[[X (1992 video game)|X]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Mario Paint]]'' (1992) - with [[Hirokazu Tanaka]] and Ryoji Yoshitomi\n*''[[Kaeru no Tame ni Kane wa Naru]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Super Mario Land 2: Six Golden Coins]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Tetris & Dr. Mario]]'' (1994) - with Hirokazu Tanaka and Yumiko Kameya\n*''[[Virtual Boy Wario Land]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Wave Race 64]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Yoshi's Story]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Mario Artist#Polygon Studio|Mario Artist: Polygon Studio]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Mario Artist#Paint Studio|Mario Artist: Paint Studio]]'' (1999) - with Chris Jojo, Martin Goodall, and Suddi Raval\n*''[[Mario Artist#Talent Studio|Mario Artist: Talent Studio]]'' (2000) - with Kenta Nagata and [[Toru Minegishi]]\n*''Machop at Work'' (2001) - with Takuto Kitsuta and Yasushi Ida\n*''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'' (2001) - with Shinobu Tanaka\n*''Kingler's Day'' (2001) - with Takuto Kitsuta and Yasushi Ida\n*''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]'' (2001) - with Kenta Nagata, Toru Minegishi, and Shinobu Tanaka\n*''[[Yoshi Touch & Go]]'' (2005) - with Asuka Ohta and Toru Minegishi\n*''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]'' (2005) - with Asuka Ohta\n*''[[Wii Menu|Default Wii Channels]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Wii Sports]]'' (2006)\n*''Kenkou Ouen Recipe 1000: DS Kondate Zenshuu'' (2006)\n*''[[X-Scape]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Wii Sports Club]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Yoshi's Woolly World]]'' (2015) - Main Theme only\n*''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Poochy & Yoshi's Woolly World]]'' (2017) - Main Theme only\n\n===Sound director/producer/supervisor===\n*''[[The Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Super Smash Bros. (video game)|Super Smash Bros.]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Pikmin 2]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Yoshi's Island DS]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Wii Sports]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Wii Music]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Luigi's Mansion: Dark Moon]]'' (2013) - with [[Koji Kondo]] and Yoji Inagaki\n*''[[Yoshi's New Island]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Mini Mario & Friends: Amiibo Challenge]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Mario Tennis Aces]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Yoshi's Crafted World]]'' (2019)\n*''[[Luigi's Mansion 3]]'' (2019)\n*''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]'' (2020)\n\n==K.K. Slider==\nThe character K.K. Slider in ''[[Animal Crossing]]'' is named Totakeke (\u3068\u305f\u3051\u3051) in the Japanese version. This name could be derived from how Totaka's name is said in Japanese, as last names usually come before personal names in the language. Totaka K. Totakeke is said to be an animal version caricature of Totaka.{{cn|date=April 2017}}\n\nAt the ''[[Mario & Zelda Big Band Live]]'' concert, some fans shouted \"Totakeke\" while the host grabbed a guitar and gave it to Totaka. Totaka then sat down on a chair like K.K. Slider while [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] held a picture of K.K. Slider next to Totaka.<ref>{{Citation|last=1Button|title=p-nintendo.com \u2014 Totaka, Mario & Zelda Big Band Live, 2003|date=2010-03-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-BCMlqslPHw|accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==Totaka's Song{{anchor|Kazumi Totaka's Song}}==\n\"Totaka's Song\" is a short, 19-note tune hidden in almost every game Totaka has written music for as an [[Easter egg (media)|Easter egg]]. It was first discovered on the title screen of ''[[Mario Paint]]'' and was later discovered as having originated in the Game Boy game ''[[X (Game Boy game)|X]]'',<ref name=\"Totaka's Song at NinDB\">{{cite news|title='Kazumi Totaka's Song'|url=http://www.nindb.net/feature/totakas-song.html| url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226195812/http://www.nindb.net/feature/totakas-song.html | archivedate=February 26, 2015 |work=NinDB}}</ref> which predated ''Mario Paint'' by two months.\n\n===Appearances===\nTotaka's song has made the following appearances:<ref name=\"Totaka's Song at NinDB\"/>\n*Many games in the ''Animal Crossing'' franchise{{ref|a|[a]}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lane |first1=Gavin |title=Feature: The Minds Behind Animal Crossing: New Horizons |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/03/feature_the_minds_behind_animal_crossing_new_horizons |website=Nintendo Life |publisher=Nlife Media |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=22 March 2020 |quote=The appearance of infamous Easter Egg Totaka's Song in Animal Crossing is perhaps the most obvious of the lot. It's called K.K. Song and Slider will usually play it on request.}}</ref>\n**''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]''\n**[[Nintendo e-Reader#Animal Crossing-e|''Animal Crossing'' e-Reader cards]] (#P13 and #P15)\n**''[[Animal Crossing: City Folk]]''\n**''[[Animal Crossing: Happy Home Designer]]''\n**''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]''\n**''[[Animal Crossing: New Leaf]]''\n**''[[Animal Crossing: Wild World]]''\n*''[[Kaeru no Tame ni Kane wa Naru]]''\n*''[[The Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening]]'', the [[The Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening#Development|''DX'' version]], and the [[The Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening (2019 video game)|2019 remake]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HLYtglYM-c0|title=Is Totaka's Song Still in Zelda: Link's Awakening? + Other Musical Easter Eggs (Game Boy vs Switch)|publisher=[[GameXplain]]|accessdate=September 13, 2019|language=English}}</ref>\n*''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'' and the [[Luigi's Mansion#Legacy|3DS remake]]\n*''[[Mario Artist|Mario Artist: Talent Studio]]''\n*''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' and [[Mario Kart 8#Mario Kart 8 Deluxe|''Mario Kart 8 Deluxe'']]<ref>{{cite web|title=Gaming Daily: Kim Jong Un Game Pulled From Kickstarter, Secret Nintendo Song Discovered in MARIO KART 8|url=https://www.nerdist.com/2015/01/gaming-daily-kim-jong-un-game-pulled-from-kickstarter-secret-nintendo-song-discovered-in-mario-kart-8/|author=Sofka, Samantha|accessdate=2015-01-12|date=2015-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113185735/https://www.nerdist.com/2015/01/gaming-daily-kim-jong-un-game-pulled-from-kickstarter-secret-nintendo-song-discovered-in-mario-kart-8/|archive-date=2015-01-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''[[Mario Paint]]''\n*''[[Pikmin 2]]''{{ref|b|[b]}} \n*''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]''\n*''[[Virtual Boy Wario Land]]''\n*''[[X (1992 video game)|X]]'', and its sequel ''[[X-Scape]]''\n*Several games in the ''Yoshi'' franchise\n**''[[Yoshi Touch & Go]]''\n**''[[Yoshi's New Island]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Video: Totaka\u2019s song in Yoshi\u2019s New Island |url=https://nintendoeverything.com/video-totakas-song-in-yoshis-new-island/ |website=Nintendo Everything |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n**''[[Yoshi's Story]]''\n\n==Characters portrayed==\n*[[Yoshi]] (first appearance in ''[[Yoshi's Story]]'')\n*Shy Guy (1998-2002)\n*[[List of Mario franchise characters#Professor E. Gadd|Professor E. Gadd]]\n*[[Captain Olimar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/nom/0405/1_2/|title=1-2 \u958b\u767a\u30b9\u30bf\u30c3\u30d5\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc|publisher=Nintendo|accessdate=July 31, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n*[[Birdo]]\n*[[K.K. Slider]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin}}\n:a. {{Note|a}}Often featured as \"K.K. Song\"\n:b. {{Note|c}}The song is only present in the GameCube release of ''Pikmin 2''. It was removed in the Wii version.\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nindb.net/feature/totakas-song-guide/index.html Kazumi Totaka's Song] at [http://www.nindb.net NinDB]\n\n{{Animal Crossing}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Totaka, Kazumi}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Japanese composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Nintendo people]]\n[[Category:Video game composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Totaka|the acharya named Totaka|Totakacharya}}\n{{Japanese name|Totaka}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Kazumi Totaka\n| image            = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1967|8|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| instrument       = [[Piano]], [[guitar]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], [[vibraphone]]\n| genre            = [[Video game music]], [[jazz]]\n| occupation       = Composer, sound director, voice actor\n| years_active     = 1990&ndash;present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| native_name      = \u6238\u9ad8\u4e00\u751f\n| Notable work     = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Kazumi Totaka'''|\u6238\u9ad8 \u4e00\u751f|Totaka Kazumi|born August 23, 1967}}<ref>{{cite book |title=Nintendo Official Guide Book \u2013 The Legend of Zelda: Link's Awakening |chapter=\u300c\u30bc\u30eb\u30c0\u306e\u4f1d\u8aac \u5922\u3092\u307f\u308b\u5cf6\u300d\u958b\u767a\u30b9\u30bf\u30c3\u30d5\u540d\u9451 |language=Japanese |page=120 |date=July 1993 |isbn=4-09-102448-3 |publisher=[[Shogakukan|Shogakukan Inc]]}}</ref> is a Japanese [[video game music|video game composer]] and sound director who is best known for his various compositions in many [[Nintendo]] games. He occasionally does voice acting as well, including [[Yoshi]] from the ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' series. He also directed the development of ''[[Wii]]\"\n\n==Works==\n\n===Composer===\n*''[[X (1992 video game)|X]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Mario Paint]]'' (1992) - with [[Hirokazu Tanaka]] and Ryoji Yoshitomi\n*''[[Kaeru no Tame ni Kane wa Naru]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Super Mario Land 2: Six Golden Coins]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Tetris & Dr. Mario]]'' (1994) - with Hirokazu Tanaka and Yumiko Kameya\n*''[[Virtual Boy Wario Land]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Wave Race 64]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Yoshi's Story]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Mario Artist#Polygon Studio|Mario Artist: Polygon Studio]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Mario Artist#Paint Studio|Mario Artist: Paint Studio]]'' (1999) - with Chris Jojo, Martin Goodall, and Suddi Raval\n*''[[Mario Artist#Talent Studio|Mario Artist: Talent Studio]]'' (2000) - with Kenta Nagata and [[Toru Minegishi]]\n*''Machop at Work'' (2001) - with Takuto Kitsuta and Yasushi Ida\n*''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'' (2001) - with Shinobu Tanaka\n*''Kingler's Day'' (2001) - with Takuto Kitsuta and Yasushi Ida\n*''[[Animal Crossing (video game)|Animal Crossing]]'' (2001) - with Kenta Nagata, Toru Minegishi, an